[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Agda is also a proof assistant based on the *propositions-as-types* paradigm (Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence), but unlike Rocq, has no separate *tactics* language, and proofs are written in a functional programming style.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The language has ordinary programming constructs such as data types, pattern matching, records, let expressions and modules, and a Haskell-like syntax.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The system has Emacs, Atom, and VS Code interfaces but can also be run in batch processing mode from a command-line interface.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Agda is based on Zhaohui Luo's unified theory of dependent types (UTT), a type theory similar to Martin-L√∂f type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Agda is named after the Swedish song "H√∂nan Agda", written by Cornelis Vreeswijk, which is about a hen named Agda.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] This alludes to the name of the theorem prover Rocq, which was originally named Coq after Thierry Coquand.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The main way of defining data types in Agda is via inductive data types which are similar to algebraic data types in non-dependently typed programming languages.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Basically, it means that there are two ways to construct a value of type $\mathbb {N}$ , representing a natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] To begin, `zero` is a natural number, and if `n` is a natural number, then `suc n`, standing for the successor of `n`, is a natural number too.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The first constructor, `z‚Č§n`, corresponds to the axiom that zero is less than or equal to any natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The second constructor, `s‚Č§s`, corresponds to an inference rule, allowing to turn a proof of `n ‚Č§ m` into a proof of `suc n ‚Č§ suc m`.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] So the value `s‚Č§s {zero} {suc zero} (z‚Č§n {suc zero})` is a proof that one (the successor of zero), is less than or equal to two (the successor of one).
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The parameters provided in curly brackets may be omitted if they can be inferred.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] In core type theory, induction and recursion principles are used to prove theorems about inductive types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] In Agda, dependently typed pattern matching is used instead.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] This way of writing recursive functions/inductive proofs is more natural than applying raw induction principles.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] In Agda, dependently typed pattern matching is a primitive of the language; the core language lacks the induction/recursion principles that pattern matching translates to.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] One of the distinctive features of Agda, when compared with other similar systems such as Rocq, is heavy reliance on metavariables for program construction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] When interacting with the system in Emacs mode, it will show the user the expected type and allow them to refine the metavariable, i.e., to replace it with more detailed code.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] This feature allows incremental program construction in a way similar to tactics-based proof assistants such as Rocq.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Programming in pure type theory involves a lot of tedious and repetitive proofs.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Although Agda has no separate tactics language, it is possible to program useful tactics within Agda.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Typically, this works by writing an Agda function that optionally returns a proof of some property of interest.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] (The pattern `()`, called *absurd*, matches if the type checker finds that its type is uninhabited, i.e. proves that it stands for a false proposition, typically because all possible constructors have arguments that are unavailable, i.e. they have unsatisfiable premisses.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Here no value of type `isJust A` can be constructed because, in that context, no value of type `A` exists to which we could apply the constructor `Just`.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The actual proof of each lemma will be automatically constructed at type-checking time.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] If the tactic fails, type-checking will fail.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Further, to write more complex tactics, Agda supports automation via reflective programming (reflection).
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The reflection mechanism allows quoting program fragments into, or unquoting them from, the abstract syntax tree.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The way reflection is used is similar to the way Template Haskell works.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Another mechanism for proof automation is proof search action in Emacs mode.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] It enumerates possible proof terms (limited to 5 seconds), and if one of the terms fits the specification, it will be put in the meta variable where the action is invoked.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] This action accepts hints, e.g., which theorems and from which modules can be used, whether the action can use pattern matching, etc.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Agda is a total functional programming language, i.e., each program in it must terminate and all possible patterns must be matched.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Without this feature, the logic behind the language becomes inconsistent, and it becomes possible to prove arbitrary statements.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] For termination checking, Agda uses the approach of the Foetus termination checker.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] Agda has an extensive de facto standard library, which includes many useful definitions and theorems about basic data structures, such as natural numbers, lists, and vectors.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The library is in beta, and is under active development.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] One of the more notable features of Agda is a heavy reliance on Unicode in program source code.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] The standard Emacs mode uses shortcuts for input, such as `\Sigma` for ő£.
[src:dependent-types-pl/agda-programming-language] There are two compiler backends, MAlonzo for Haskell and one for JavaScript.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] In mathematical logic and computer science, the **calculus of constructions** (**CoC**) is a type theory created by Thierry Coquand.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] It can serve as both a typed programming language and as constructive foundation for mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] For this second reason, the CoC and its variants have been the basis for Rocq and other proof assistants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] Some of its variants include the calculus of inductive constructions (which adds inductive types), the calculus of (co)inductive constructions (which adds coinduction), and the predicative calculus of inductive constructions (which removes some impredicativity).
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The CoC is a higher-order typed lambda calculus, initially developed by Thierry Coquand.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] It is well known for being at the top of Barendregt's lambda cube.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] It is possible within CoC to define functions from terms to terms, terms to types, types to types, and from types to terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The CoC is strongly normalizing, and hence consistent.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The CoC has been developed alongside the Rocq proof assistant.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] As features were added (or possible liabilities removed) to the theory, they became available in Rocq.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] Variants of the CoC are used in other proof assistants, such as Matita and Lean.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The calculus of constructions can be considered an extension of the Curry‚ÄďHoward isomorphism.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The Curry‚ÄďHoward isomorphism associates a term in the simply typed lambda calculus with each natural-deduction proof in intuitionistic propositional logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The calculus of constructions extends this isomorphism to proofs in the full intuitionistic predicate calculus, which includes proofs of quantified statements (which we will also call "propositions").
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] 5. $\mathbf {T}$ itself, which is the type of large types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] As with the untyped lambda calculus, the calculus of constructions uses a basic notion of equivalence of terms, known as $\beta$ -equivalence.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The valid judgments for the calculus of constructions are derivable from a set of inference rules.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] In the following, we use $\Gamma$ to mean a sequence of type assignments $x_{1}:A_{1},x_{2}:A_{2},\ldots$ ; $A,B,C,D$ to mean terms; and $K,L$ to mean either $\mathbf {P}$ or $\mathbf {T}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] We shall write $B[x:=N]$ to mean the result of substituting the term N for the free variable x in the term B .
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] The calculus of constructions has very few basic operators: the only logical operator for forming propositions is $\forall$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] Booleans and Naturals are defined in the same way as in Church encoding.
[src:dependent-types-pl/calculus-of-inductive-constructions] However, added problems arise from propositional extensionality and proof irrelevance.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In computer science and logic, a **dependent type** is a type whose definition depends on a value.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] It is an overlapping feature of type theory and type systems.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In intuitionistic type theory, dependent types are used to encode logic's quantifiers like "for all" and "there exists".
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In functional programming languages like Agda, ATS, Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), F*, Epigram, Idris, and Lean, dependent types help reduce bugs by enabling the programmer to assign types that further restrain the set of possible implementations.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Two common examples of dependent types are *dependent functions* and *dependent pairs*.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The return type of a dependent function may depend on the *value* (not just type) of one of its arguments.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For instance, a function that takes a positive integer n may return an array of length n , where the array length is part of the type of the array.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] (Note that this is different from polymorphism and generic programming, both of which include the type as an argument.) A dependent pair may have a second value, the type of which depends on the first value.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Sticking with the array example, a dependent pair may be used to pair an array with its length in a type-safe way.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Dependent types add complexity to a type system.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Deciding the equality of dependent types in a program may require computations.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In 1934, Haskell Curry noticed that the types used in typed lambda calculus, and in its combinatory logic counterpart, followed the same pattern as axioms in propositional logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Going further, for every proof in the logic, there was a matching function (term) in the programming language.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] One of Curry's examples was the correspondence between simply typed lambda calculus and intuitionistic logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Predicate logic is an extension of propositional logic, adding quantifiers.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Howard and de Bruijn extended lambda calculus to match this more powerful logic by creating types for dependent functions, which correspond to "for all", and dependent pairs, which correspond to "there exists".
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Because of this, and other work by Howard, propositions-as-types is known as the Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In dependent type theory, a dependent type is a type whose specification may vary with a value, and can be viewed as analogous to an indexed family of sets.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Let ${\mathcal {U}}$ denote a universe of types, and write $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ to indicate that A is a type in ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] A dependent **family of types** over A is written $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , meaning that to each term $a:A$ the family assigns a type $B(a):{\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Thus, given $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , the expression $B(a)$ denotes a type that depends on the particular value a .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In standard terminology, this is described by saying that the type $B(a)$ varies with a .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] A function whose type of return value varies with its argument (i.e. there is no fixed codomain) is a **dependent function** and the type of this function is called **dependent product type**, **pi-type** (**ő† type**) or **dependent function type**.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] From a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ we may construct the type of dependent functions ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ , whose terms are functions that take a term $a:A$ and return a term in $B(a)$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For this example, the dependent function type is typically written as ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ or ${\textstyle \prod {(x:A)}B(x)}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] If $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ is a constant function, the corresponding dependent product type is equivalent to an ordinary function type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] That is, ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B}$ is judgmentally equal to $A\to B$ when B does not depend on x .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The name 'ő†-type' comes from the idea that these may be viewed as a Cartesian product of types. ő†-types can also be understood as models of universal quantifiers.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For example, if we write $\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)$ for *n*-tuples of real numbers, then ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)}$ would be the type of a function which, given a natural number n, returns a tuple of real numbers of size n.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The usual function space arises as a special case when the range type does not actually depend on the input.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] E.g. ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }{\mathbb {R} }}$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to the real numbers, which is written as $\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {R}$ in typed lambda calculus.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The dual of the dependent product type is the **dependent pair type**, **dependent sum type**, **sigma-type**, or (confusingly) **dependent product type**.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Sigma-types can also be understood as existential quantifiers.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Continuing the above example, if, in the universe of types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , there is a type $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , then there is a dependent pair type ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The dependent pair type captures the idea of an ordered pair where the type of the second term is dependent on the value of the first.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] If B is a constant function, then the dependent pair type becomes (is judgmentally equal to) the product type, that is, an ordinary Cartesian product $A\times B$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For a more concrete example, taking A to again be type of unsigned integers from 0 to 255, and $B(a)$ to again be equal to $X_{a}$ for 256 more arbitrary $X_{a}$ , then ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ devolves into the sum $X_{0}+X_{1}+X_{2}+\ldots +X_{253}+X_{254}+X_{255}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Let $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ be some type, and let $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] By the Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence, B can be interpreted as a logical predicate on terms of A .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For a given $a:A$ , whether the type $B(a)$ is inhabited indicates whether a satisfies this predicate.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The correspondence can be extended to existential quantification and dependent pairs: the proposition $\exists {a}{\in }A\,B(a)$ is true if and only if the type ${\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B(a)}$ is inhabited.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] For example, $m:\mathbb {N}$ is less than or equal to $n:\mathbb {N}$ if and only if there exists another natural number $k:\mathbb {N}$ such that $m+k=n$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] That is, a proof of the statement that m is less than or equal to n is a pair that contains both a non-negative number k , which is the difference between m and n , and a proof of the equality $m+k=n$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] Henk Barendregt developed the lambda cube as a means of classifying type systems along three axes.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The eight corners of the resulting cube-shaped diagram each correspond to a type system, with simply typed lambda calculus in the least expressive corner, and calculus of constructions in the most expressive.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The three axes of the cube correspond to three different augmentations of the simply typed lambda calculus: the addition of dependent types, the addition of polymorphism, and the addition of higher kinded type constructors (functions from types to types, for example).
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The lambda cube is generalized further by pure type systems.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi$ of pure first order dependent types, corresponding to the logical framework LF, is obtained by generalising the function space type of the simply typed lambda calculus to the dependent product type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi 2$ of second order dependent types is obtained from $\lambda \Pi$ by allowing quantification over type constructors.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] In this theory the dependent product operator subsumes both the $\to$ operator of simply typed lambda calculus and the $\forall$ binder of System F.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The higher order system $\lambda \Pi \omega$ extends $\lambda \Pi 2$ to all four forms of abstraction from the lambda cube: functions from terms to terms, types to types, terms to types and types to terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The system corresponds to the calculus of constructions whose derivative, the calculus of inductive constructions is the underlying system of Rocq.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence implies that types can be constructed that express arbitrarily complex mathematical properties.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] If the user can supply a constructive proof that a type is *inhabited* (i.e., that a value of that type exists) then a compiler can check the proof and convert it into executable computer code that computes the value by carrying out the construction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The proof checking feature makes dependently typed languages closely related to proof assistants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/dependent-type] The code-generation aspect provides a powerful approach to formal program verification and proof-carrying code, since the code is derived directly from a mechanically verified mathematical proof.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The Idris type system is similar to Agda's.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Compared to Agda, Idris prioritizes management of side effects and support for embedded domain-specific languages.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris is compiled by modular backends, which provide code generation and a runtime system.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The Idris compiler includes backends for Chez Scheme, Racket, JavaScript (both browser- and Node.js-based), and C.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Additional third-party backends are available for other platforms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris is named after a singing dragon from the 1970s UK children's television programme *Ivor the Engine*.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris combines a number of features from relatively mainstream functional programming languages with features borrowed from proof assistants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The syntax of Idris shows many similarities with that of Haskell.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The only differences between this program and its Haskell equivalent are the single (instead of double) colon in the type signature of the main function, and the omission of the word "`where`" in the module declaration.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris supports inductively-defined data types and parametric polymorphism.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] With dependent types, it is possible for values to appear in the types; in effect, any value-level computation can be performed during type checking.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The function `append` appends a vector of `m` elements of type `a` to a vector of `n` elements of type `a`.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Since the precise types of the input vectors depend on a value, it is possible to be certain at compile time that the resulting vector will have exactly (`n` + `m`) elements of type `a`.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The word "`total`" invokes the totality checker which will report an error if the function doesn't cover all possible cases or cannot be (automatically) proven not to enter an infinite loop.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] `Num` a signifies that the type a belongs to the type class `Num`.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Note that this function still typechecks successfully as total, even though there is no case matching `Nil` in one vector and a number in the other.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Because the type system can prove that the vectors have the same length, we can be sure at compile time that case will not occur and there is no need to include that case in the function‚Äôs definition.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Dependent types are powerful enough to encode most properties of programs, and an Idris program can prove invariants at compile time.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] This makes Idris into a proof assistant.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] There are two standard ways of interacting with proof assistants: by writing a series of tactic invocations (Rocq style), or by interactively elaborating a proof term (Epigram‚ÄďAgda style).
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris supports both modes of interaction, although the set of available tactics is not yet as useful as that of Rocq.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Because Idris contains a proof assistant, Idris programs can be written to pass proofs around.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] If treated na√Įvely, such proofs remain around at runtime.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris aims to avoid this pitfall by aggressively erasing unused terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] By default, Idris generates native code through C.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] The other officially supported backend generates JavaScript.
[src:dependent-types-pl/idris-programming-language] Idris 2 is a new self-hosted version of the language which deeply integrates a linear type system, based on quantitative type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] In type theory, a system has **inductive types** if it has facilities for creating a new type from constants and functions that create terms of that type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The feature serves a role similar to data structures in a programming language and allows a type theory to add concepts like numbers, relations, and trees.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] As the name suggests, inductive types can be self-referential, but usually only in a way that permits structural recursion.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The standard example is encoding the natural numbers using Peano's encoding.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Here, a natural number is created either from the constant "O" (representing zero) or by applying the function "S" to another natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] "S" is the successor function which represents adding one to a number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Thus, "S O" is one, "S (S O)" is two, "S (S (S O))" is three, and so on.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Since their introduction, inductive types have been extended to encode more and more structures, while still being predicative and supporting structural recursion.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Inductive types usually come with a function to prove properties about them.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] In words: for any predicate "P" over natural numbers, given a proof of "P O" and a proof of "P n -> P (n+1)", we get back a proof of "forall n, P n".
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] This is the familiar induction principle for natural numbers.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] W-types are well-founded types in intuitionistic type theory (ITT).
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] They generalize natural numbers, lists, binary trees, and other "tree-shaped" data types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Given a type *A* : *U* and a dependent family *B* : *A* ‚Üí *U*, one can form a W-type ${\mathsf {W}}_{a:A}B(a)$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The type *A* may be thought of as "labels" for the (potentially infinitely many) constructors of the inductive type being defined, whereas *B* indicates the (potentially infinite) arity of each constructor.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] M-types) may also be understood as well-founded (resp. non-well-founded) trees with nodes labeled by elements *a* : *A* and where the node labeled by *a* has *B*(*a*)-many subtrees.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Each W-type is isomorphic to the initial algebra of a so-called polynomial functor.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] One may define the natural numbers as the W-type $\mathbb {N$ with *f* : **2** ‚Üí *U* is defined by *f*(1**2**) = **0** (representing the constructor for zero, which takes no arguments), and *f*(2**2**) = **1** (representing the successor function, which takes one argument).
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The value of $f(\operatorname {inl} (1_{\mathbf {1} }))$ corresponds to the constructor for the empty list, whereas the value of $f(\operatorname {inr} (a))$ corresponds to the constructor that appends *a* to the beginning of another list.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The elimination rule for W-types works similarly to structural induction on trees.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] If, whenever a property (under the propositions-as-types interpretation) $C:{\mathsf {W}}_{x:A}B(x)\to U$ holds for all subtrees of a given tree it also holds for that tree, then it holds for all trees.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] In extensional type theories, W-types (resp.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] M-types) can be defined up to isomorphism as initial algebras (resp. final coalgebras) for polynomial functors.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] In this case, the property of initiality (res. finality) corresponds directly to the appropriate induction principle.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] In intensional type theories with the univalence axiom, this correspondence holds up to homotopy (propositional equality).
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] M-types are dual to W-types, and represent coinductive (potentially infinite) data such as streams.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] This technique allows *some* definitions of multiple types that depend on each other.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Induction-recursion started as a study into the limits of ITT.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Once found, the limits were turned into rules that allowed defining new inductive types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] These types could depend upon a function and the function on the type, as long as both were defined simultaneously.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Universe types can be defined using induction-recursion.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Induction-induction allows definition of a type and a family of types at the same time.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] So, a type A and a family of types $B:A\to Type$ .
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] This is a current research area in Homotopy type theory (HoTT).
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] This differs from ITT by its identity type (equality).
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] Higher inductive types define a new type with constants and functions that create elements of the type, and new instances of the identity type that relate them.
[src:dependent-types-pl/inductive-type] The existence of a new constructor for the identity type makes circle a higher inductive type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In mathematical logic, and theoretical computer science, **type theory** is the study of formal systems that classify expressions or mathematical objects by their *types*.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Roughly speaking, a type plays a similar role to that played by a data type in programming: it specifies what kind of thing an expression is and how it may be used.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theories are used in the study of programming languages (type systems), formal logic, and the formalization of mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some type theories have been proposed as alternatives to set theory as a foundation of mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Examples include Alonzo Church's simple theory of types and Per Martin-L√∂f's intuitionistic type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Many proof assistants are based on type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, the underlying formal language of Rocq (formerly Coq) is the calculus of inductive constructions, while Lean is based on dependent type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theory was created to avoid paradoxes in naive set theory and formal logic, such as Russell's paradox which demonstrates that, without proper axioms, it is possible to define the set of all sets that are not members of themselves; this set both contains itself and does not contain itself.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Between 1902 and 1908, Bertrand Russell proposed various solutions to this problem.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] By 1908, Russell arrived at a ramified theory of types together with an axiom of reducibility, both of which appeared in Whitehead and Russell's *Principia Mathematica* published in 1910, 1912, and 1913.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This system avoided contradictions suggested in Russell's paradox by creating a hierarchy of types and then assigning each concrete mathematical entity to a specific type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Entities of a given type were built exclusively of subtypes of that type, thus preventing an entity from being defined using itself.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This resolution of Russell's paradox is similar to approaches taken in other formal systems, such as Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theory is particularly popular in conjunction with Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] One notable early example of type theory is Church's simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Church's theory of types helped the formal system avoid the Kleene‚ÄďRosser paradox that afflicted the original untyped lambda calculus.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Church demonstrated that it could serve as a foundation of mathematics and it was referred to as a higher-order logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In the modern literature, "type theory" refers to a typed system based around lambda calculus.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] One influential system is Per Martin-L√∂f's intuitionistic type theory, which was proposed as a foundation for constructive mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Another is Thierry Coquand's calculus of constructions, which is used as the foundation by Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), Lean, and other computer proof assistants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theory is an active area of research, one direction being the development of homotopy type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The first computer proof assistant, called Automath, used type theory to encode mathematics on a computer.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Martin-L√∂f specifically developed intuitionistic type theory to encode *all* mathematics to serve as a new foundation for mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] There is ongoing research into mathematical foundations using homotopy type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Mathematicians working in category theory already had difficulty working with the widely accepted foundation of Zermelo‚ÄďFraenkel set theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This led to proposals such as Lawvere's Elementary Theory of the Category of Sets (ETCS).
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Homotopy type theory continues in this line using type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Researchers are exploring connections between dependent types (especially the identity type) and algebraic topology (specifically homotopy).
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Much of the current research into type theory is driven by proof checkers, interactive proof assistants, and automated theorem provers.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Many type theories are supported by LEGO and Isabelle.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Isabelle also supports foundations besides type theories, such as ZFC.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Mizar is an example of a proof system that only supports set theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Any static program analysis, such as the type checking algorithms in the semantic analysis phase of compiler, has a connection to type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A prime example is Agda, a programming language which uses UTT (Luo's Unified Theory of dependent Types) for its type system.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The programming language ML was developed for manipulating type theories (see *Logic for Computable Functions*) and its own type system was heavily influenced by them.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theory is also widely used in formal theories of semantics of natural languages, especially Montague grammar and its descendants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In particular, categorial grammars and pregroup grammars extensively use type constructors to define the types (*noun*, *verb*, etc.) of words.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A complex type $\langle a,b\rangle$ is the type of functions from entities of type a to entities of type ‚Ā† b ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Thus one has types like $\langle e,t\rangle$ that are interpreted as elements of the set of functions from entities to truth-values, i.e. indicator functions of sets of entities.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] An expression of type $\langle \langle e,t\rangle ,t\rangle$ is a function from sets of entities to truth-values, i.e. a (indicator function of a) set of sets.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This latter type is standardly taken to be the type of natural language quantifiers, like *everybody* or *nobody* (Montague 1973, Barwise and Cooper 1981).
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theory with records is a formal semantics representation framework, using *records* to express *type theory types*.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] It has been used in natural language processing, principally computational semantics and dialogue systems.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Gregory Bateson introduced a theory of logical types into the social sciences; his notions of double bind and logical levels are based on Russell's theory of types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A type theory is a mathematical logic, which is to say it is a collection of rules of inference that result in judgments.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Most logics have judgments asserting "The proposition $\varphi$ is true", or "The formula $\varphi$ is a well-formed formula".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A type theory has judgments that define types and assign them to a collection of formal objects, known as terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A term and its type are often written together as ‚Ā† $\mathrm {term$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A term in logic is recursively defined as a constant symbol, variable, or a function application, where a term is applied to another term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Constant symbols could include the natural number ‚Ā† 0 ‚Ā†, the Boolean value ‚Ā† ${\texttt {true}}$ ‚Ā†, and functions such as the successor function $\mathrm {S}$ and conditional operator ‚Ā† $\mathrm {if}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, one might say "assuming x is a term of type ${\mathsf {bool}}$ and y is a term of type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, it follows that $({\textrm {if}}\,x\,y\,y)$ is a term of type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Such judgments are formally written with the turnstile symbol ‚Ā† $\vdash$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] If there are no assumptions, there will be nothing to the left of the turnstile.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The list of assumptions on the left is the *context* of the judgment.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Capital greek letters, such as $\Gamma$ and $\Delta$ , are common choices to represent some or all of the assumptions.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The 4 different judgments are thus usually written as follows.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some textbooks use a triple equal sign $\equiv$ to stress that this is judgmental equality and thus an extrinsic notion of equality.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The judgments enforce that every term has a type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type will restrict which rules can be applied to a term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A type theory's inference rules say what judgments can be made, based on the existence of other judgments.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Rules are expressed as a Gentzen-style deduction using a horizontal line, with the required input judgments above the line and the resulting judgment below the line.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, the following inference rule states a substitution rule for judgmental equality. ${\begin{array}{c}\Gamma \vdash t:T_{1}\qquad \Delta \vdash T_{1}=T_{2}\\\hline \Gamma ,\Delta \vdash t:T_{2}\end{array}}$ The rules are syntactic and work by rewriting.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The metavariables ‚Ā† $\Gamma$ ‚Ā†, ‚Ā† $\Delta$ ‚Ā†, ‚Ā† t ‚Ā†, ‚Ā† $T_{1}$ ‚Ā†, and ‚Ā† $T_{2}$ ‚Ā† may actually consist of complex terms and types that contain many function applications, not just single symbols.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] To generate a particular judgment in type theory, there must be a rule to generate it, as well as rules to generate all of that rule's required inputs, and so on.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The applied rules form a proof tree, where the top-most rules need no assumptions.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] One example of a rule that does not require any inputs is one that states the type of a constant term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Generally, the desired conclusion of a proof in type theory is one of type inhabitation.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Girard's paradox shows that type inhabitation is strongly related to the consistency of a type system with Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] To be sound, such a system must have uninhabited types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For examples of rules, an interested reader may follow Appendix A.2 of the *Homotopy Type Theory* book, or read Martin-L√∂f's Intuitionistic Type Theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The logical framework of a type theory bears a resemblance to intuitionistic, or constructive, logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Formally, type theory is often cited as an implementation of the Brouwer‚ÄďHeyting‚ÄďKolmogorov interpretation of intuitionistic logic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Additionally, connections can be made to category theory and computer programs.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] When used as a foundation, certain types are interpreted to be propositions (statements that can be proven), and terms inhabiting the type are interpreted to be proofs of that proposition.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] When some types are interpreted as propositions, there is a set of common types that can be used to connect them to make a Boolean algebra out of types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] However, the logic is not classical logic but intuitionistic logic, which is to say it does not have the law of excluded middle nor double negation.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Because the law of excluded middle does not hold, there is no term of type ‚Ā† $\Pi A.A+(A\to \bot )$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Likewise, double negation does not hold, so there is no term of type ‚Ā† $\Pi A.((A\to \bot )\to \bot )\to A$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] It is possible to include the law of excluded middle and double negation into a type theory, by rule or assumption.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] However, terms may not compute down to canonical terms and it will interfere with the ability to determine if two terms are judgementally equal to each other.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Per Martin-L√∂f proposed his intuitionistic type theory as a foundation for constructive mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Constructive mathematics requires when proving "there exists an x with property ‚Ā† $P(x)$ ‚Ā†", one must construct a particular x and a proof that it has property P .
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In type theory, existence is accomplished using the dependent product type, and its proof requires a term of that type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] An example of a non-constructive proof is proof by contradiction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The first step is assuming that x does not exist and refuting it by contradiction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The conclusion from that step is "it is not the case that x does not exist".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The last step is, by double negation, concluding that x exists.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Constructive mathematics does not allow the last step of removing the double negation to conclude that x exists.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Most of the type theories proposed as foundations are constructive, and this includes most of the ones used by proof assistants.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] It is possible to add non-constructive features to a type theory, by rule or assumption.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] These include operators on continuations such as call with current continuation.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] However, these operators tend to break desirable properties such as canonicity and parametricity.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence is the observed similarity between logics and programming languages.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The implication in logic, "A $\to$ B" resembles a function from type "A" to type "B".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For a variety of logics, the rules are similar to expressions in a programming language's types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The similarity goes farther, as applications of the rules resemble programs in the programming languages.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Thus, the correspondence is often summarized as "proofs as programs".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The opposition of terms and types can also be viewed as one of *implementation* and *specification*.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] By program synthesis, (the computational counterpart of) type inhabitation can be used to construct (all or parts of) programs from the specification given in the form of type information.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Many programs that work with type theory (e.g., interactive theorem provers) also do type inferencing.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] It lets them select the rules that the user intends, with fewer actions by the user.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Although the initial motivation for category theory was far removed from foundationalism, the two fields turned out to have deep connections.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The interplay, known as categorical logic, has been a subject of active research since then; see the monograph of Jacobs (1999) for instance.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Homotopy type theory attempts to combine type theory and category theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] It focuses on equalities, especially equalities between types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Homotopy type theory differs from intuitionistic type theory mostly by its handling of the equality type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In 2016, cubical type theory was proposed, which is a homotopy type theory with normalization.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The most basic types are called atoms, and a term whose type is an atom is known as an atomic term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Common atomic terms included in type theories are natural numbers, often notated with the type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, Boolean logic values (‚Ā† ${\texttt {true}}$ ‚Ā† and ‚Ā† ${\texttt {false}}$ ‚Ā†), notated with the type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {bool}}$ ‚Ā†, and formal variables, whose type may vary.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, the following may be atomic terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In addition to atomic terms, most modern type theories also allow for functions.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Function types introduce an arrow symbol, and are defined inductively: If $\sigma$ and $\tau$ are types, then the notation $\sigma \to \tau$ is the type of a function which takes a parameter of type $\sigma$ and returns a term of type ‚Ā† $\tau$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Types of this form are known as *simple* types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some terms may be declared directly as having a simple type, such as the following term, ‚Ā† $\mathrm {add}$ ‚Ā†, which takes in two natural numbers in sequence and returns one natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Strictly speaking, a simple type only allows for one input and one output, so a more faithful reading of the above type is that $\mathrm {add}$ is a function which takes in a natural number and returns a function of the form ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}\to {\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The parentheses clarify that $\mathrm {add}$ does not have the type ‚Ā† $({\mathsf {nat}}\to {\mathsf {nat}})\to {\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, which would be a function which takes in a function of natural numbers and returns a natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The convention is that the arrow is right associative, so the parentheses may be dropped from ‚Ā† $\mathrm {add}$ ‚Ā†'s type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] New function terms may be constructed using lambda expressions, and are called lambda terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] These terms are also defined inductively: a lambda term has the form ‚Ā† $(\lambda v.t)$ ‚Ā†, where v is a formal variable and t is a term, and its type is notated ‚Ā† $\sigma \to \tau$ ‚Ā†, where $\sigma$ is the type of ‚Ā† v ‚Ā†, and $\tau$ is the type of ‚Ā† t ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The following lambda term represents a function which doubles an input natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The variable is x and (implicit from the lambda term's type) must have type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The term $\mathrm {add} \,x\,x$ has type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, which is seen by applying the function application inference rule twice.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Thus, the lambda term has type ${\mathsf {nat}}\to {\mathsf {nat}}$ , which means it is a function taking a natural number as an argument and returning a natural number.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A lambda term is an anonymous function because it lacks a name.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The concept of anonymous functions appears in many programming languages.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The power of type theories is in specifying how terms may be combined by way of inference rules.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theories which have functions also have the inference rule of function application: if t is a term of type ‚Ā† $\sigma \to \tau$ ‚Ā†, and s is a term of type ‚Ā† $\sigma$ ‚Ā†, then the application of t to ‚Ā† s ‚Ā†, often written ‚Ā† $(t\,s)$ ‚Ā†, has type ‚Ā† $\tau$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, if one knows the type notations ‚Ā† $0:{\textsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, ‚Ā† $1:{\textsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, and ‚Ā† $2:{\textsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†, then the following type notations can be deduced from function application.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Parentheses indicate the order of operations; however, by convention, function application is left associative, so parentheses can be dropped where appropriate.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In the case of the three examples above, all parentheses could be omitted from the first two, and the third may simplified to ‚Ā† $\mathrm {add} \,1\,(\mathrm {add} \,2\,0):{\textsf {nat}}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theories that allow for lambda terms also include inference rules known as $\beta$ -reduction and $\eta$ -reduction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] They generalize the notion of function application to lambda terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The first reduction describes how to evaluate a lambda term: if a lambda expression $(\lambda v.t)$ is applied to a term ‚Ā† s ‚Ā†, one replaces every occurrence of v in t with ‚Ā† s ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The second reduction makes explicit the relationship between lambda expressions and function types: if $(\lambda v.t\,v)$ is a lambda term, then it must be that t is a function term because it is being applied to ‚Ā† v ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Therefore, the lambda expression is equivalent to just ‚Ā† t ‚Ā†, as both take in one argument and apply t to it.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, the following term may be $\beta$ -reduced.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In type theories that also establish notions of equality for types and terms, there are corresponding inference rules of $\beta$ -equality and $\eta$ -equality.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type is usually written $\bot$ or ‚Ā† $\mathbb {0}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] One use for the empty type is proofs of type inhabitation.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] If for a type ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†, it is consistent to derive a function of type ‚Ā† $a\to \bot$ ‚Ā†, then a is *uninhabited*, which is to say it has no terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The unit type has exactly 1 canonical term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type is written $\top$ or $\mathbb {1}$ and the single canonical term is written ‚Ā† $\ast$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The unit type is also used in proofs of type inhabitation.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] If for a type ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†, it is consistent to derive a function of type ‚Ā† $\top \to a$ ‚Ā†, then a is *inhabited*, which is to say it must have one or more terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The Boolean type has exactly 2 canonical terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type is usually written ${\textsf {bool}}$ or $\mathbb {B}$ or ‚Ā† $\mathbb {2}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The canonical terms are usually $\mathrm {true}$ and ‚Ā† $\mathrm {false}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Natural numbers are usually implemented in the style of Peano Arithmetic.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] There is a canonical term $0:{\mathsf {nat}}$ for zero.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Canonical values larger than zero use iterated applications of a successor function ‚Ā† $\mathrm {S$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some type theories allow for types of complex terms, such as functions or lists, to depend on the types of its arguments; these are called type constructors.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, a type theory could have the dependent type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {list}}\,a$ ‚Ā†, which should correspond to lists of terms, where each term must have type ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In this case, ${\mathsf {list}}$ has the kind ‚Ā† $U\to U$ ‚Ā†, where U denotes the universe of all types in the theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The product type, ‚Ā† $\times$ ‚Ā†, depends on two types, and its terms are commonly written as ordered pairs ‚Ā† $(s,t)$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The pair $(s,t)$ has the product type ‚Ā† $\sigma \times \tau$ ‚Ā†, where $\sigma$ is the type of s and $\tau$ is the type of ‚Ā† t ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Each product type is then usually defined with eliminator functions $\mathrm {first$ and ‚Ā† $\mathrm {second$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Besides ordered pairs, this type is used for the concepts of logical conjunction and intersection.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The sum type is written as either + or ‚Ā† $\sqcup$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In programming languages, sum types may be referred to as tagged unions.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The sum type is used for the concepts of logical disjunction and union.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some theories also allow terms to have their definitions depend on types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For instance, an identity function of any type could be written as ‚Ā† $\lambda x.x:\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The function is said to be polymorphic in ‚Ā† $\alpha$ ‚Ā†, or generic in ‚Ā† x ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] As another example, consider a function ‚Ā† $\mathrm {append}$ ‚Ā†, which takes in a ${\mathsf {list}}\,a$ and a term of type ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†, and returns the list with the element at the end.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type annotation of such a function would be ‚Ā† $\mathrm {append$ ‚Ā†, which can be read as "for any type ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†, pass in a ${\mathsf {list}}\,a$ and an ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†, and return a ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {list}}\,a$ ‚Ā†".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Here $\mathrm {append}$ is polymorphic in ‚Ā† a ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] With polymorphism, the eliminator functions can be defined generically for *all* product types as $\mathrm {first$ and ‚Ā† $\mathrm {second$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some theories also permit types to be dependent on terms instead of types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, a theory could have the type ‚Ā† ${\mathsf {vector}}\,n$ ‚Ā†, where n is a term of type ${\mathsf {nat}}$ encoding the length of the vector.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This allows for greater specificity and type safety: functions with vector length restrictions or length matching requirements, such as the dot product, can encode this requirement as part of the type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] There are foundational issues that can arise from dependent types if a theory is not careful about what dependences are allowed, such as Girard's Paradox.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The logician Henk Barendegt introduced the lambda cube as a framework for studying various restrictions and levels of dependent typing.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Two common type dependences, dependent product and dependent sum types, allow for the theory to encode BHK intuitionistic logic by acting as equivalents to universal and existential quantification; this is formalized by Curry‚ÄďHoward correspondence.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] As they also connect to products and sums in set theory, they are often written with the symbols $\Pi$ and ‚Ā† $\Sigma$ ‚Ā†, respectively.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Sum types are seen in dependent pairs, where the second type depends on the value of the first term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This arises naturally in computer science where functions may return different types of outputs based on the input.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, the Boolean type is usually defined with an eliminator function ‚Ā† $\mathrm {if}$ ‚Ā†, which takes three arguments and behaves as follows.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Ordinary definitions of $\mathrm {if}$ require x and y to have the same type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The type of $\mathrm {if}$ may then be written as ‚Ā† $\forall \,\sigma \,\tau .\Pi _{x:{\mathsf {bool}}}.\sigma \to \tau \to \mathrm {TF} \,x\,\sigma \,\tau$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Following the notion of Curry‚ÄďHoward Correspondence, the identity type is a type introduced to mirror propositional equivalence, as opposed to the judgmental (syntactic) equivalence that type theory already provides.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] An identity type requires two terms of the same type and is written with the symbol ‚Ā† = ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For example, if $x+1$ and $1+x$ are terms, then $x+1=1+x$ is a possible type.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Canonical terms are created with a reflexivity function, ‚Ā† $\mathrm {refl}$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] For a term ‚Ā† t ‚Ā†, the call $\mathrm {refl} \,t$ returns the canonical term inhabiting the type ‚Ā† $t=t$ ‚Ā†.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The complexities of equality in type theory make it an active research topic; homotopy type theory is a notable area of research that mainly deals with equality in type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Inductive types are a general template for creating a large variety of types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In fact, all the types described above and more can be defined using the rules of inductive types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Two methods of generating inductive types are induction-recursion and induction-induction.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] A method that only uses lambda terms is Scott encoding.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some proof assistants, such as Rocq (previously known as *Coq*) and Lean, are based on the calculus for inductive constructions, which is a calculus of constructions with inductive types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The most commonly accepted foundation for mathematics is first-order logic with the language and axioms of Zermelo‚ÄďFraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice, abbreviated ZFC.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Type theories having sufficient expressibility may also act as a foundation of mathematics.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] There are a number of differences between these two approaches.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Proponents of type theory will also point out its connection to constructive mathematics through the BHK interpretation, its connection to logic by the Curry‚ÄďHoward isomorphism, and its connections to category theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] However, there are type theories that define "subtyping".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Computation takes place by repeated application of rules.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Many types of theories are strongly normalizing, which means that any order of applying the rules will always end in the same result.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] In a normalizing type theory, the one-directional computation rules are called "reduction rules", and applying the rules "reduces" the term.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] If a rule is not one-directional, it is called a "conversion rule".
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Some combinations of types are equivalent to other combinations of types.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] When functions are considered "exponentiation", the combinations of types can be written similarly to algebraic identities.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This is because a type theory is defined by its rules of inference.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This is a source of confusion for people familiar with Set Theory, where a theory is defined by both the rules of inference for a logic (such as first-order logic) and axioms about sets.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Sometimes, a type theory will add a few axioms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] An axiom is a judgment that is accepted without a derivation using the rules of inference.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] They are often added to ensure properties that cannot be added cleanly through the rules.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] Axioms can cause problems if they introduce terms without a way to compute on those terms.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] That is, axioms can interfere with the normalizing property of the type theory.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The axiom of choice does not need to be added to type theory, because in most type theories it can be derived from the rules of inference.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] This is because of the constructive nature of type theory, where proving that a value exists requires a method to compute the value.
[src:dependent-types-pl/type-theory] The axiom of choice is less powerful in type theory than most set theories, because type theory's functions must be computable and, being syntax-driven, the number of terms in a type must be countable.
